00:00:15.682 --> 00:00:17.100 position:50% align:center
[STUDENT 1A] You think
you can just pick a fight

00:00:17.183 --> 00:00:18.518 position:50% align:center
and then walk away?

00:00:18.601 --> 00:00:20.145 position:50% align:center
[KURESAWA] I'm not
trying to fight with you.

00:00:20.228 --> 00:00:23.148 position:50% align:center
[STUDENT 1B] Sorry, it's too
late for the innocent routine!

00:00:23.231 --> 00:00:24.733 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Is this really happening?

00:00:24.816 --> 00:00:27.736 position:50% align:center
I usually only see people get
bullied like this in manga!

00:00:27.819 --> 00:00:29.279 position:50% align:center
But it's kind of
cliche nowadays,

00:00:29.362 --> 00:00:31.531 position:50% align:center
even for Boys' Love stories!

00:00:31.614 --> 00:00:32.866 position:50% align:center
[HIRANO]
What's up, Miyano?

00:00:32.949 --> 00:00:34.576 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO] Hirano! I'm behind
the south building

00:00:34.659 --> 00:00:36.870 position:50% align:center
and there's a student
getting beat up by three guys!

00:00:36.953 --> 00:00:38.204 position:50% align:center
I don't know what I should do!

00:00:38.288 --> 00:00:39.330 position:50% align:center
[thud]

00:00:41.166 --> 00:00:43.001 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
I have to stop this!

00:00:44.169 --> 00:00:45.295 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
Hey.

00:00:48.214 --> 00:00:51.051 position:50% align:center
You hold this.
I'll go and break it up.

00:00:51.134 --> 00:00:53.094 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Huh? Who's he?

00:00:54.054 --> 00:00:54.804 position:50% align:center
But--

00:00:54.888 --> 00:00:55.889 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
Here.

00:00:59.017 --> 00:01:00.852 position:50% align:center
[STUDENT 1A]
Huh? What do you want?

00:01:00.935 --> 00:01:02.687 position:50% align:center
I'm here to clean up.

00:01:02.771 --> 00:01:04.147 position:50% align:center
Hey, you okay?

00:01:04.230 --> 00:01:05.231 position:50% align:center
You should get out of here.

00:01:05.315 --> 00:01:06.691 position:50% align:center
[KURESAWA]
Um, thanks.

00:01:06.775 --> 00:01:08.485 position:50% align:center
[STUDENT 1B]
Are you kidding me with this?

00:01:11.112 --> 00:01:13.656 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO] I admired my
upperclassman in secret

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:16.284 position:50% align:center
as I watched him
march into the fray.

00:01:21.164 --> 00:01:24.959 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
Miyano! Good morning!

00:01:25.877 --> 00:01:27.629 position:50% align:center
Good morning, Sasaki.

00:01:28.797 --> 00:01:31.925 position:50% align:center
Look at you, Mya,
you're as cute as ever today.

00:01:32.008 --> 00:01:33.134 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Will you cut it out?

00:01:33.218 --> 00:01:35.303 position:50% align:center
For the hundredth time:
don't call me cute.

00:01:35.387 --> 00:01:37.806 position:50% align:center
You know I'm self-conscious
about how feminine my face is.

00:01:37.889 --> 00:01:39.516 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI] Fine, then you're
an inner-cutie!

00:01:39.599 --> 00:01:42.268 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO] Not really the
adjustment I was hoping for.

00:01:45.438 --> 00:01:47.816 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
How did we end up like this?

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:03.998 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO] Recently,
Sasaki's been overdoing it

00:02:04.082 --> 00:02:06.418 position:50% align:center
with the physical contact.

00:02:06.501 --> 00:02:08.878 position:50% align:center
Hey, Mya! What's up?

00:02:08.962 --> 00:02:10.797 position:50% align:center
You want me to
put you in slash art?

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:13.008 position:50% align:center
'Cause I'll do it
if you don't cut it out!

00:02:13.091 --> 00:02:15.051 position:50% align:center
Go right ahead,
it doesn't bother me!

00:02:15.135 --> 00:02:16.803 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Well, it would bother me!

00:02:17.762 --> 00:02:20.015 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
By the way, what's slash art?

00:02:20.098 --> 00:02:22.142 position:50% align:center
It's probably better
if you stay in the dark.

00:02:22.225 --> 00:02:24.519 position:50% align:center
And please don't ask your
friends about it, either.

00:02:24.602 --> 00:02:26.312 position:50% align:center
Wait, is slash art
related to "moe"?

00:02:26.396 --> 00:02:28.481 position:50% align:center
Or that "seme" or
"uke" stuff, maybe?

00:02:28.565 --> 00:02:29.774 position:50% align:center
I can never keep track.

00:02:29.858 --> 00:02:31.943 position:50% align:center
No! Those words are
way more embarrassing

00:02:32.027 --> 00:02:34.029 position:50% align:center
coming from a non-otaku's mouth!

00:02:34.112 --> 00:02:35.989 position:50% align:center
Oh yeah, you like manga, right?

00:02:36.072 --> 00:02:37.699 position:50% align:center
Got any good recs?

00:02:37.782 --> 00:02:39.075 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Here we go.

00:02:39.159 --> 00:02:41.870 position:50% align:center
Normies always end up
asking for recommendations.

00:02:41.953 --> 00:02:45.665 position:50% align:center
I dunno, what kind of manga
are you usually into, Sasaki?

00:02:45.749 --> 00:02:49.210 position:50% align:center
Well, I guess recently
I was kind of digging

00:02:49.294 --> 00:02:52.589 position:50% align:center
this cool shoujo series
that my sister was reading.

00:02:52.672 --> 00:02:55.258 position:50% align:center
But I want to try
something you like.

00:03:00.680 --> 00:03:02.807 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO] Okay, but this
is all I have on me!

00:03:02.891 --> 00:03:05.977 position:50% align:center
Oh, you don't mind if
I borrow it? Thanks a ton!

00:03:06.061 --> 00:03:07.062 position:50% align:center
But you have to promise me that

00:03:07.145 --> 00:03:08.813 position:50% align:center
you'll only look at it
in your room!

00:03:08.897 --> 00:03:10.774 position:50% align:center
And whatever you do, you can't
take it out of the bag

00:03:10.857 --> 00:03:12.025 position:50% align:center
unless you're alone!

00:03:12.108 --> 00:03:13.985 position:50% align:center
Basically, treat it like
it's a toxic substance!

00:03:14.069 --> 00:03:15.820 position:50% align:center
Also, I don't want you
to assume anything about me

00:03:15.904 --> 00:03:17.280 position:50% align:center
just because I like
reading this stuff.

00:03:17.364 --> 00:03:18.448 position:50% align:center
I mean, not that there's
anything wrong...

00:03:18.531 --> 00:03:20.450 position:50% align:center
Right. I get it.

00:03:21.493 --> 00:03:23.995 position:50% align:center
[meows]

00:03:26.164 --> 00:03:27.582 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
Good morning, Mya.

00:03:29.751 --> 00:03:32.462 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Hey, Sasaki, how's it going?

00:03:32.545 --> 00:03:34.839 position:50% align:center
That manga from
yesterday. I read it.

00:03:34.923 --> 00:03:36.966 position:50% align:center
Yeah? And what did
you think of it?

00:03:37.050 --> 00:03:38.426 position:50% align:center
I liked that one part
at the end where

00:03:38.510 --> 00:03:40.220 position:50% align:center
the two guys were
in the hotel together--

00:03:40.303 --> 00:03:42.013 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Shh-shh-shh-shh-shh!

00:03:42.097 --> 00:03:44.140 position:50% align:center
Look, rule number one!

00:03:44.224 --> 00:03:45.350 position:50% align:center
No matter what, you should never

00:03:45.433 --> 00:03:46.768 position:50% align:center
discuss that kind
of subject matter

00:03:46.851 --> 00:03:48.937 position:50% align:center
in front of random people
at school, do you hear me?

00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:50.605 position:50% align:center
It's way too awkward!

00:03:50.689 --> 00:03:52.691 position:50% align:center
Oh, uh, sure thing, sorry.

00:03:54.192 --> 00:03:56.653 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI] Well, now that
it's just you and me.

00:03:56.736 --> 00:03:58.822 position:50% align:center
I can't exactly say
I have any experience

00:03:58.905 --> 00:04:00.615 position:50% align:center
reading that kind of manga.

00:04:00.699 --> 00:04:04.160 position:50% align:center
So yeah, it caught me off guard
at first, but I really liked it!

00:04:07.914 --> 00:04:11.960 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI] At first, I assumed it
was a typical detective story.

00:04:12.043 --> 00:04:13.878 position:50% align:center
But then the romance between
the two guys started

00:04:13.962 --> 00:04:16.464 position:50% align:center
and it was really good!

00:04:16.548 --> 00:04:18.008 position:50% align:center
I liked how in
spite of everything

00:04:18.091 --> 00:04:19.551 position:50% align:center
the main character
was dealing with,

00:04:19.634 --> 00:04:22.095 position:50% align:center
he pushed through
and made it work.

00:04:22.178 --> 00:04:23.179 position:50% align:center
And then by the end,

00:04:23.263 --> 00:04:25.348 position:50% align:center
he ended up way stronger
because of it.

00:04:26.641 --> 00:04:29.436 position:50% align:center
It was a great story.
I loved it.

00:04:31.479 --> 00:04:33.606 position:50% align:center
Right? It's so good, isn't it?

00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:35.025 position:50% align:center
What did you think of the uke?

00:04:35.108 --> 00:04:36.443 position:50% align:center
That's what they call
the more submissive character

00:04:36.526 --> 00:04:38.028 position:50% align:center
in the BL pairing, in case
you didn't know that term.

00:04:38.111 --> 00:04:39.446 position:50% align:center
Uh, okay.

00:04:39.529 --> 00:04:41.197 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO] The uke is
usually small and cute

00:04:41.281 --> 00:04:42.574 position:50% align:center
and kind of a crybaby,

00:04:42.657 --> 00:04:43.700 position:50% align:center
but sometimes,
he turns out to be

00:04:43.783 --> 00:04:45.910 position:50% align:center
the more masculine
half of the couple!

00:04:47.996 --> 00:04:50.790 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
Uh, right, got it.

00:04:50.874 --> 00:04:54.252 position:50% align:center
So, the part at the end.
I liked that a lot, too.

00:04:54.336 --> 00:04:55.712 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Oh, yeah, same here!

00:04:55.795 --> 00:04:57.547 position:50% align:center
Actually, if I had to pick
a favorite moment

00:04:57.630 --> 00:04:59.716 position:50% align:center
of the whole manga,
that would be the one!

00:04:59.799 --> 00:05:01.885 position:50% align:center
I think it's a really nice way
to express how happy

00:05:01.968 --> 00:05:04.346 position:50% align:center
the characters are in
that moment, don't you?

00:05:05.138 --> 00:05:07.182 position:50% align:center
Yeah, definitely.

00:05:07.265 --> 00:05:10.518 position:50% align:center
I wasn't sure what you would
say about it, since it's BL,

00:05:10.602 --> 00:05:11.770 position:50% align:center
but I'm so happy to hear...

00:05:11.853 --> 00:05:13.146 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
Damn it.

00:05:14.147 --> 00:05:15.815 position:50% align:center
The author's
one of my favorites.

00:05:15.899 --> 00:05:18.109 position:50% align:center
She writes about couples who are
so different from each other

00:05:18.193 --> 00:05:20.320 position:50% align:center
and shows them being
so happy together!

00:05:20.403 --> 00:05:22.697 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
He's so cute.

00:05:22.781 --> 00:05:26.201 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
Hey, uh... Mya?

00:05:26.284 --> 00:05:27.952 position:50% align:center
What's up?

00:05:28.036 --> 00:05:29.954 position:50% align:center
Lend me another one.

00:05:30.038 --> 00:05:31.039 position:50% align:center
Uh--

00:05:34.959 --> 00:05:36.211 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
Delivery for Mya!

00:05:36.294 --> 00:05:37.712 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Wait, what?

00:05:37.796 --> 00:05:39.547 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO] Lately, he's been
stopping by to see me so much

00:05:39.631 --> 00:05:42.384 position:50% align:center
that it's starting to
feel a bit excessive.

00:05:42.467 --> 00:05:43.593 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI] I want you to
have these cookies

00:05:43.677 --> 00:05:45.595 position:50% align:center
that I made in cooking class.

00:05:45.679 --> 00:05:46.721 position:50% align:center
Thanks for the manga.

00:05:46.805 --> 00:05:48.973 position:50% align:center
Oh. Thanks, that's nice.

00:05:49.057 --> 00:05:51.810 position:50% align:center
They're not super-sweet though.
I hope you don't mind.

00:05:51.893 --> 00:05:54.771 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO] Actually, I'm not into
sweets anyway, so it's perfect.

00:05:54.854 --> 00:05:57.315 position:50% align:center
[SASAKI]
Oh, great! Later, then.

00:06:00.985 --> 00:06:03.405 position:50% align:center
What was that?
Didn't know the two of you had

00:06:03.488 --> 00:06:05.657 position:50% align:center
a "homemade cookies"
level relationship.

00:06:05.740 --> 00:06:06.908 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
It's not like that!

00:06:06.991 --> 00:06:08.910 position:50% align:center
Isn't he a delinquent
or something, though?

00:06:08.993 --> 00:06:10.870 position:50% align:center
You sure he's not bad news?

00:06:10.954 --> 00:06:15.208 position:50% align:center
Seriously, it's okay.
He's actually a really nice guy.

00:06:15.291 --> 00:06:18.545 position:50% align:center
[TASHIRO]
Mm... If you say so.

00:06:22.215 --> 00:06:23.133 position:50% align:center
Miyano?

00:06:23.216 --> 00:06:24.801 position:50% align:center
[MIYANO]
Hi, Hirano!

00:06:24.884 --> 00:06:26.469 position:50% align:center
[HIRANO] Listen,
I noticed Sasaki's been

00:06:26.553 --> 00:06:28.888 position:50% align:center
visiting your classroom
a lot recently.

00:06:28.972 --> 00:06:30.140 position:50% align:center
